domain

Class BitSequence

  • java.lang.Object
    • domain.BitSequence

  • public class BitSequence
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a sequence of bits of arbitrary length.

    • Constructor Summary

      Constructors 
      Constructor and Description
      BitSequence()
      Returns an instance of BitSequence of length zero.
      BitSequence(byte[] bits, int freeBits)
      Returns an instance of BitSequence corresponding to the bits contained in the given array (excluding the last n bits of the last byte in the array, where n is given by parameter freeBits).
      BitSequence(byte[] bits, int freeBits, int writeIndex)
      Returns an instance of BitSequence corresponding to the bits contained in the given array, up to bits[writeIndex] (excluding the last n bits of byte bits[writeIndex], where n is given by parameter freeBits).
      BitSequence(long lengthInBits)
      Returns an instance of BitSequence of length indicated by lengthInBits; all the bits in the sequence will be set to zero.

    • Constructor Detail

      • BitSequence

        public BitSequence()
        Returns an instance of BitSequence of length zero.

      • BitSequence

        public BitSequence(long lengthInBits)
        Returns an instance of BitSequence of length indicated by lengthInBits; all the bits in the sequence will be set to zero.
        Parameters:
        lengthInBits - The length in bits of the bit sequence; it must between 0 (inclusive) and Integer.MAX_VALUE * Byte.SIZE (exclusive).

      • BitSequence

        public BitSequence(byte[] bits,
                   int freeBits)
        Returns an instance of BitSequence corresponding to the bits contained in the given array (excluding the last n bits of the last byte in the array, where n is given by parameter freeBits). Will set the free bits of bits[bits.length - 1] to zero. Be careful, since the bits array (given as parameter) isn't copied, instead it is used and modified directly (until it needs to be resized).
        Parameters:
        bits - Byte array containing the bits of the bit sequence.
        freeBits - Amount of free bits in the last byte of the array; it can have values ranging from 0 to Byte.SIZE (both inclusive).

      • BitSequence

        public BitSequence(byte[] bits,
                   int freeBits,
                   int writeIndex)
        Returns an instance of BitSequence corresponding to the bits contained in the given array, up to bits[writeIndex] (excluding the last n bits of byte bits[writeIndex], where n is given by parameter freeBits). Will set bits[i] = 0 for all i which are greater than writeIndex. Be careful, since the bits array (given as parameter) isn't copied, instead it is used and modified directly (until it needs to be resized).
        Parameters:
        bits - Byte array containing the bits of the bit sequence.
        freeBits - Amount of free bits of byte bits[writeIndex]; it can have values ranging from 0 to Byte.SIZE (both inclusive).
        writeIndex - Index of last byte of array bits (given as a parameter) containing bits of the bit sequence; it can have values ranging from 0 (inclusive) to bits.length (exclusive).

      • append

        public void append(BitSequence otherBS)
        Appends the bit sequence given as parameter to the end of this bit sequence.

      • append

        public void append(int codeword,
                   int bitLength)
        Appends to the end of this bit sequence the n rightmost bits (where n is given by bitLength) of the binary representation of the given integer (which represents a LZW codeword). The parameters are not checked, so be sure to call this with legal values (see the parameters' description).
        Parameters:
        codeword - Represents a LZW codeword.
        bitLength - The numbers of leftmost bits (of codeword's binary representation) which will be appended to the end of this bit sequence. It can have values ranging from 1 (inclusive) to Integer.SIZE (inclusive).

      • readNextBit

        public java.lang.Boolean readNextBit()
        Reads the value of the bit at the current reading position, then increments the reading position by one.
        Returns:
        False for 0, true for 1.

      • readNextInt

        public java.lang.Integer readNextInt(int bitLength)
        Reads the next n bits (where n is given by parameter bitLength) starting at the current reading position, interpreting them as an integer, then increments the reading position by n places (where n is given by parameter bitLength). The parameter is not checked, so be sure to call this with legal values (see the parameter's description).
        Parameters:
        bitLength - The number of bits to be read; it can have values ranging from 9 (inclusive) to Integer.SIZE (inclusive).
        Returns:
        An integer which corresponds to the read bits.

      • nextSequence

        public BitSequence nextSequence()
        Returns the bit sequence corresponding to the next binary number. The returned sequence will have the same length of this one (thus preserving possible leading zeros), except when the next binary number cannot be represented with the same amount of bits (in that case, the returned sequence will be one bit longer).
        Returns:
        Bit sequence corresponding to the next binary number.

      • setReadPosition

        public void setReadPosition(int readIndex,
                            int readOffset)
        Sets the reading position to the given read position (specified by parameters readIndex and readOffset).
        Parameters:
        readIndex - Index of the byte array used internally to store the bit sequence; read position will be set at this index.
        readOffset - Offset (into the byte at readIndex) of the bit to which the read position will be set; it can have values ranging from 0 (most significant bit on the left) to Byte.SIZE - 1 (least significant bit on the right).
